<TITLE> PM concerned over trafficking </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Apr 22 (bdnews24.com)  Prime minister Sheikh Hasina has expressed concern over women and children's trafficking and has asked for appropriate actions to prevent it. She also ordered strict measures to stop drug smuggling and the use of children in this illicit activity. Hasina gave these orders at the inaugural meeting of a 48-member National Women and Child Development Council at the Prime Minister's Office on Thursday. The PM asked for more awareness campaigns and formation of strict law to prevent child abuse. While presiding over the meeting, Hasina said that the activities of Women's Affairs Department and National Women's Association in every upazila must be strengthened. She also suggested that women vice presidents at every upazila should be involved in the process. Hasina said that there should be new initiatives in education and training for the re-habilitation of street children. The PM stressed on building more dormitories and day-care centers to help women cope with their working schedule and solve their accommodation problem. She urged for more support and training to make poor women self dependent. Hasina said that assistance to single women, widows or women deserted by their husbands, should be prioritised. She said, "There should be more cooperation among the different projects of the women and children affairs ministry." Agriculture minister Matia Chowdhury, planning minister AK Khandakar, law minister Shafique Ahmed, home minister Sahara Khatun, information minister Abul Kalam Azad, social welfare minister Enamul Haque Mostafa Shahid, health minister Ruhal Haque, ICT state minister Yafes Osman, environment state minister Hasan Mahmud, women MPs Tarana Halim, Sayeda Jebunnesa and Shadhana Haldar, education specialist Mumtaz Hossain, journalist Baby Moudud, Tania Bakht and others were present at the meeting. b
